Alright, alright, alright.

166
00:10:39,880 --> 00:10:41,400
Show me the money.

167
00:10:41,920 --> 00:10:44,400
Show me the money,
as Cuba Gooding used to say !

168
00:10:47,280 --> 00:10:50,440
Moving on.
Our main story concerns the police.

169
00:10:50,840 --> 00:10:55,160
As these cops show frequently have
to deal with humanity at its worst.

170
00:10:56,000 --> 00:10:57,640
What's the first amendment ?

171
00:10:58,320 --> 00:11:03,320
What's the first amendment ?
You don't even know !

172
00:11:06,640 --> 00:11:08,560
Constitutiooooon !

173
00:11:09,160 --> 00:11:12,000
Yeah. Constitution ! Read it !

174
00:11:12,680 --> 00:11:14,480
And live by it.

175
00:11:14,600 --> 00:11:16,760
Let's have a seat
in the back of the car.

176
00:11:18,840 --> 00:11:20,360
Ron Paul 2012 !

177
00:11:23,400 --> 00:11:27,240
That's perfect. It's not like
he needed to say "Ron Paul 2012".

178
00:11:27,600 --> 00:11:30,680
That was implicit in everything
he said up to that point.

179
00:11:30,760 --> 00:11:33,320
But it's certainly nice
to have it confirmed.

180
00:11:33,400 --> 00:11:36,920
The police have been at the center
of a great deal of controversy.

181
00:11:37,200 --> 00:11:41,640
From the Black Lives Matter movement,
to Colin Kaepernick's protest,

182
00:11:41,720 --> 00:11:46,040
to Mary J. Blige awkwardly singing
a Springsteen song at Hillary Clinton.

183
00:11:46,760 --> 00:11:51,960
Is it a gun,
is it a knife, is it a wallet,

184
00:11:52,160 --> 00:11:53,680
this is your life ?

185
00:11:54,120 --> 00:11:56,920
You can get killed
just for living in

186
00:11:59,160 --> 00:12:02,560
your American skin.

187
00:12:07,400 --> 00:12:08,560
Hillary, thank you !

188
00:12:10,320 --> 00:12:11,760
God !

189
00:12:13,000 --> 00:12:15,280
Hillary would have won
my undying respect

190
00:12:15,360 --> 00:12:18,600
if she'd looked Mary J. Blige
straight in the face and said:

191
00:12:18,680 --> 00:12:21,760
"I support your message,
but that was awkward as fuck".

192
00:12:21,840 --> 00:12:25,120
"And I wish you hadn't done it".
That would've been honest.

193
00:12:25,200 --> 00:12:28,360
The trust between police
and the communities they serve

194
00:12:28,440 --> 00:12:31,080
is clearly a cornerstone
of civilized society.

195
00:12:31,160 --> 00:12:35,480
That trust has been rocked following
controversial police shootings

196
00:12:35,560 --> 00:12:39,000
from Alton Sterling,
to Philando Castile, to Tamir Rice,

197
00:12:39,080 --> 00:12:42,240
to so many others,
I literally cannot mention them all.

198
00:12:42,320 --> 00:12:46,760
These deaths, taken with countless
smaller incidents of police misconduct,

199
00:12:46,840 --> 00:12:48,640
have led to a common refrain.

200
00:12:49,400 --> 00:12:52,160
I just want the police
to be held accountable.

201
00:12:52,440 --> 00:12:55,400
We want the system of policing
to be held accountable.

202
00:12:55,800 --> 00:12:59,480
Those police
need to be held accountable.

203
00:12:59,720 --> 00:13:03,120
Whenever they commit a crime,
whenever something goes wrong,

204
00:13:03,200 --> 00:13:06,560
and I'm talking about serious stuff
like murder and whatnot,

205
00:13:06,640 --> 00:13:08,560
these guys never get prosecuted.

206
00:13:09,120 --> 00:13:12,440
Now those are valid frustrations.
Although, as a side note:

207
00:13:12,520 --> 00:13:16,120
"Murder and Whatnot"
would be an amazing CSI spinoff.

208
00:13:16,360 --> 00:13:18,440
That's a watchable show right there.

209
00:13:19,000 --> 00:13:22,560
Police accountability is what we're
going to be talking about.

210
00:13:22,640 --> 00:13:25,640
I should say,
as the police will tell you,

211
00:13:25,760 --> 00:13:29,000
they have a difficult,
dangerous, challenging job.

212
00:13:29,400 --> 00:13:32,120
No reasonable person
would disagree with that.

213
00:13:32,200 --> 00:13:35,800
That's all the more reason
for ensuring that it's done perfectly.

214
00:13:35,880 --> 00:13:40,280
The worst thing that happens
if a cake decorator fucks up

215
00:13:40,360 --> 00:13:43,320
is you end up wishing someone
a Happy Analversary.

216
00:13:44,000 --> 00:13:46,800
While that's obviously not ideal,
who knows ?

217
00:13:47,160 --> 00:13:49,160
Maybe it's their analversary, too !

218
00:13:50,480 --> 00:13:54,920
The police will argue that what they
have is less an institutional problem,

219
00:13:55,000 --> 00:13:56,880
than it is an individual one.

220
00:13:57,640 --> 00:14:00,200
There's been
some bad apples out there.

221
00:14:00,280 --> 00:14:04,360
I don't think that that is indicative
of the entire police department.

222
00:14:04,440 --> 00:14:07,640
But you got bad apples
in every occupation.

223
00:14:07,800 --> 00:14:10,000
You're gonna have some bad apples.

224
00:14:10,280 --> 00:14:14,480
They're out to protect you
and that's what policing's about.

225
00:14:14,800 --> 00:14:20,120
That is a weirdly blasÃ© attitude.
Bad apples can erode trust fast.

226
00:14:20,200 --> 00:14:22,320
Snow White wasn't afraid of apples

227
00:14:22,400 --> 00:14:25,400
before she took a bite
out of that one really bad one,

228
00:14:25,480 --> 00:14:29,000
but the next time an old lady
comes at her with a piece of fruit,

229
00:14:29,120 --> 00:14:31,360
Snow is gonna
get the fuck out of there.

230
00:14:32,200 --> 00:14:36,800
That argument "it's a few bad apples"
has some real problems.

231
00:14:36,880 --> 00:14:39,800
For a start, it doesn't address
bad laws and policies

232
00:14:39,880 --> 00:14:42,080
that good officers
are made to enforce

233
00:14:42,160 --> 00:14:44,800
which we've touched
on multiple times before.

234
00:14:44,880 --> 00:14:47,920
Criminal justice is kind
of our show's signature bit.

235
00:14:48,280 --> 00:14:51,680
It is to us what assessing
the shape of your poop is to Dr. Oz.

236
00:14:52,760 --> 00:14:56,000
Also, you can't claim
there's just a few bad apples,

237
00:14:56,080 --> 00:14:58,640
when no one knows exactly
how many there are.

238
00:14:59,040 --> 00:15:02,160
There are nearly 18 000
police departments in America,

239
00:15:02,240 --> 00:15:05,280
and they are not great
about reporting or sharing data.

240
00:15:05,360 --> 00:15:09,320
Even some surprisingly
basic questions are hard to answer,

241
00:15:09,400 --> 00:15:11,440
as the head of the FBI admits.

242
00:15:12,280 --> 00:15:15,560
We can't have an informed discussion,
we don't have data.

243
00:15:15,640 --> 00:15:19,320
People have data about who went to
a movie, how many books were sold,

244
00:15:19,400 --> 00:15:22,440
how many cases of the flu
walked into an emergency room.

245
00:15:22,520 --> 00:15:25,840
I cannot tell you how many people
were shot by police in the US

246
00:15:25,920 --> 00:15:29,280
last month, last year,
or anything about the demographics.

247
00:15:30,200 --> 00:15:33,760
How is that possible ? We have
numbers for almost everything !

248
00:15:33,920 --> 00:15:38,240
We have ratings for how many people
watched Jeremy Piven in "Mr. Selfridge"

249
00:15:38,480 --> 00:15:42,240
The government tracks how many
people are killed by falling TVs

250
00:15:42,320 --> 00:15:45,760
a number inflated by people
who were watching "Mr. Selfridge"

251
00:15:45,880 --> 00:15:49,680
and said "I choose death", and then
pulled the TV down on top of them.

252
00:15:51,320 --> 00:15:57,200
The best numbers on police misconduct
come from a researcher, Philip Stinson,

253
00:15:57,280 --> 00:15:59,880
who accumulated
over a decade's worth of data

254
00:15:59,960 --> 00:16:03,680
by setting up 48 Google alerts
in 2005.

255
00:16:03,760 --> 00:16:07,160
Google Alerts.
And his stats are truly chilling.

256
00:16:07,240 --> 00:16:10,840
Out of thousands of fatal
police shootings since 2005,

257
00:16:10,920 --> 00:16:14,840
only 77 officers have been charged
with murder or manslaughter.

258
00:16:14,920 --> 00:16:18,440
And to date,
only 26 have been convicted.

259
00:16:18,520 --> 00:16:22,080
And while the truth is,
many police shootings are justified,

260
00:16:22,160 --> 00:16:25,800
26 seems suspiciously low.

261
00:16:25,880 --> 00:16:29,640
So: how can that be the number ?
Well, broadly speaking,

262
00:16:29,720 --> 00:16:33,640
most investigations of police
misconduct face a few obstacles.

263
00:16:33,720 --> 00:16:38,080
And the first one is big: misconduct
is often investigated internally,

264
00:16:38,160 --> 00:16:41,720
by an officer's colleagues,
which does not inspire confidence.

265
00:16:41,800 --> 00:16:46,200
But if you listen to the police chief
in Bakersfield, the system is fine.

266
00:16:47,000 --> 00:16:51,160
You're confident that that structure
of review is entirely impartial ?

267
00:16:51,560 --> 00:16:53,800
I am.
These guys are expert in their field.

268
00:16:54,000 --> 00:16:56,120
They're part of the departments.

269
00:16:56,320 --> 00:17:01,600
They have hundreds of years of law
enforcement experience combined.

270
00:17:01,920 --> 00:17:05,440
Here's the thing there.
Combined experience is not a thing

271
00:17:05,520 --> 00:17:08,080
that automatically
makes you do a better job.

272
00:17:08,160 --> 00:17:12,080
Our staff has a combined
347 years in television

273
00:17:12,160 --> 00:17:15,800
and that doesn't mean we won't
throw a fuckload of raisins on a desk

274
00:17:15,880 --> 00:17:17,520
and call it entertainment.

275
00:17:18,760 --> 00:17:24,040
The DOJ has consistently found
flaws with internal investigations.

276
00:17:24,120 --> 00:17:28,520
In Cleveland, investigators admitted
they intentionally cast an officer

277
00:17:28,600 --> 00:17:32,400
in the best light possible when
investigating a use of deadly force.

278
00:17:32,640 --> 00:17:36,600
In Miami, investigations took so long
that "at least two officers"

279
00:17:36,680 --> 00:17:41,360
"killed a suspect while still under
investigation for a previous shooting".

280
00:17:41,800 --> 00:17:44,840
And there should never be
a second one of anything

281
00:17:44,960 --> 00:17:48,000
before you figure out
whether the first was justified.

282
00:17:48,080 --> 00:17:53,280
Call it the "Dolphin Tale 2" rule.
How is there a second one of these ?

283
00:17:54,120 --> 00:17:58,040
I thought Harry Connick Jr. ate the
dolphin at the end of the first one.

284
00:17:58,480 --> 00:18:00,720
I don't know for sure,
I haven't seen it.

285
00:18:00,800 --> 00:18:03,360
But no one has
and that's the point.

286
00:18:04,600 --> 00:18:08,400
In Baltimore, the DOJ report included
the story of Joe Crystal,

287
00:18:08,560 --> 00:18:12,800
a detective who reported two fellow
officers for alleged excessive force,

288
00:18:12,880 --> 00:18:14,320
and was labeled a "rat",

289
00:18:14,480 --> 00:18:17,840
with one colleague leaving pictures
of cheese on his desk,

290
00:18:18,160 --> 00:18:20,280
which is almost charming,

291
00:18:21,160 --> 00:18:23,680
until you learn
how far some others went.

292
00:18:24,080 --> 00:18:28,920
He found himself cut off. He didn't
get backup in dangerous situations.

293
00:18:29,120 --> 00:18:32,080
Someone left a dead rat
on his windshield.

294
00:18:32,480 --> 00:18:37,480
It was like their way of telling me:
you don't belong here...

295
00:18:38,240 --> 00:18:43,120
Leaving a dead rat on an officer's
windshield is hostile.

296
00:18:43,360 --> 00:18:45,920
Unless of course,
that officer is a police cat,

297
00:18:46,280 --> 00:18:49,520
in which case it means:
"Welcome to the force, Whiskers !"

298
00:18:49,760 --> 00:18:52,440
"We're lucky to have you !
Enjoy the rat."

299
00:18:53,720 --> 00:18:57,960
Accountability doesn't just suffer
from an unwritten code of silence.

300
00:18:58,040 --> 00:19:02,200
That code can be enshrined
within state laws or union contracts.

301
00:19:02,320 --> 00:19:06,840
It's hard to spot problem officers
because, in many jurisdictions,

302
00:19:07,200 --> 00:19:10,400
policies allow disciplinary
records to be destroyed.

303
00:19:10,800 --> 00:19:13,120
In Baton Rouge,
a sustained complaint

304
00:19:13,360 --> 00:19:16,840
can be stricken from
your record after just 18 months.

305
00:19:17,240 --> 00:19:20,480
And in Mesa, Arizona, when
a journalist demanded records,

306
00:19:20,600 --> 00:19:24,760
a police chief made an internal video
reminding his officers

307
00:19:24,880 --> 00:19:27,680
that there was a way
for them to clean up their past.

308
00:19:28,240 --> 00:19:33,120
I don't want anybody to relive
a problem they've been disciplined for,

309
00:19:33,240 --> 00:19:36,240
that has already seen the scrutiny
in the public eye.

310
00:19:36,400 --> 00:19:39,600
Purge your files according to policy,

311
00:19:39,680 --> 00:19:44,160
make sure the things you don't
want in there aren't in there.

312
00:19:44,840 --> 00:19:46,760
That seems wrong.

313
00:19:46,920 --> 00:19:50,600
You should not be able to erase parts
of your past that are damning.

314
00:19:50,680 --> 00:19:54,440
This is an official police file,
not a Volkswagen corporate history

315
00:19:54,520 --> 00:19:56,840
that somehow starts
after World War II.

316
00:19:57,440 --> 00:20:01,560
Nazi cars. The choice of the Nazis.

317
00:20:03,040 --> 00:20:07,640
Deleting records is not an officer's
only option to escape their past.

318
00:20:07,720 --> 00:20:13,080
After an incident, they'll resign,
and move to another department.

319
00:20:13,160 --> 00:20:17,000
It happens so much, people in law
enforcement call them "gypsy cops".

320
00:20:17,280 --> 00:20:20,320
In South Carolina, a TV station
looked into one officer

321
00:20:20,400 --> 00:20:24,680
who spent a total of nine years
working for nine departments,

322
00:20:24,800 --> 00:20:29,840
three of them in one year, and in one
case, he left in spectacular fashion.

323
00:20:30,360 --> 00:20:33,640
Deputies believed Yarbrough's
driving was "compromised"

324
00:20:33,720 --> 00:20:36,960
and they discovered a half-empty
"bottle of rye whiskey"

325
00:20:37,040 --> 00:20:40,080
and a baggie of "assorted pills"
in his patrol cruiser.

326
00:20:40,360 --> 00:20:45,760
Yarbrough said: "I'm not taking
no drug test, I guess I'll resign."

327
00:20:46,560 --> 00:20:51,400
Holy shit. "I'm not taking no
drug test, I guess I'll resign"

328
00:20:51,480 --> 00:20:54,640
is a sentence you do not want
to hear from a police officer.

329
00:20:54,720 --> 00:20:57,960
It's barely appropriate from
a roadie leaving Aerosmith.

330
00:20:59,120 --> 00:21:03,080
"Gypsy cops" have been involved
in tragic incidents.

331
00:21:03,160 --> 00:21:06,560
In the Tamir Rice case, the officer
who shot the 12-year-old

332
00:21:06,640 --> 00:21:10,600
had been in the process
of being fired, before resigning.

333
00:21:10,880 --> 00:21:14,680
But, the Cleveland police missed
that red flag when hiring him,

334
00:21:14,920 --> 00:21:17,000
they didn't read
his personnel file,

335
00:21:17,080 --> 00:21:19,160
an incident
during weapons training

336
00:21:19,240 --> 00:21:23,160
where he had a loss of composure,
leading his supervisor to conclude:

337
00:21:23,240 --> 00:21:28,520
"I do not believe time, nor training,
will change or correct deficiencies."

338
00:21:28,920 --> 00:21:33,760
That performance review should keep
you from getting hired at Staples,

339
00:21:34,120 --> 00:21:36,720
let alone a job
where you're given a gun.

340
00:21:37,480 --> 00:21:41,680
That cop was never even charged.
Like many such cases,

341
00:21:41,920 --> 00:21:44,080
his never made it past
the grand jury.

342
00:21:44,200 --> 00:21:48,320
Which seems inherently surprising,
until you realize:

343
00:21:48,520 --> 00:21:54,040
local prosecutors and cops have to work
together, which can get complicated.

344
00:21:54,520 --> 00:21:58,960
As a former prosecutor,
you rely upon the police.

345
00:21:59,040 --> 00:22:03,800
You trust the police. The police
are in your office examining evidence,

346
00:22:03,880 --> 00:22:05,200
preparing for trial.

347
00:22:05,280 --> 00:22:08,920
And then have to turn around and
prosecute them to prosecute you.

348
00:22:09,200 --> 00:22:14,160
Exactly. For a prosecutor to go
after a cop they work with is awkward.

349
00:22:14,240 --> 00:22:19,360
I can't think of anything more
awkward, other than this:

350
00:22:23,680 --> 00:22:24,920
Hillary, thank you.

351
00:22:25,600 --> 00:22:31,080
God, it's not getting any better.
Nothing in Hillary's life

352
00:22:31,200 --> 00:22:33,240
has ever been
more awkward than that.

353
00:22:33,360 --> 00:22:36,040
Think about
what a high bar that is.

354
00:22:38,040 --> 00:22:42,240
Even when cases go to trial,
officers have a major advantage,

355
00:22:42,480 --> 00:22:46,120
juries tend to have a natural
predisposition to trust them.

356
00:22:46,640 --> 00:22:49,400
Police officers get a presumption
of innocence

357
00:22:49,480 --> 00:22:54,920
whereas most criminal defendants don't
come in with presumption of innocence.

358
00:22:55,040 --> 00:22:57,840
A judge will toss the case
at a preliminary hearing

359
00:22:57,920 --> 00:23:01,680
or a grand jury will refuse to indict,
so you never even get to trial.

360
00:23:01,960 --> 00:23:05,640
Jurors do not come in
with any belief

361
00:23:05,720 --> 00:23:09,280
that officers can commit a crime.

362
00:23:09,520 --> 00:23:14,360
Many people see a police uniform
and think "trustworthy".

363
00:23:14,680 --> 00:23:17,720
Unless it includes a sleeveless shirt
and a boom-box,

364
00:23:17,880 --> 00:23:19,960
in which case
they think "stripper".

365
00:23:20,040 --> 00:23:23,080
And sometimes: "Wait... Jim ?
From middle school ?!"

366
00:23:24,840 --> 00:23:30,640
The police have a certain amount of
leeway regarding lethal force,

367
00:23:30,720 --> 00:23:33,800
meaning that "fatal shootings
can be considered legal"

368
00:23:33,880 --> 00:23:36,800
"even if they are
unnecessary or disproportional."

369
00:23:36,880 --> 00:23:41,360
There is even a shorthand
for such cases, lawful but awful.

370
00:23:41,640 --> 00:23:45,080
Which is also the legal
definition of Woody Allen's marriage.

371
00:23:46,120 --> 00:23:49,440
I think that's it.
Who are you angry with here ?

372
00:23:51,360 --> 00:23:53,200
Put the boos
back in your pocket.

373
00:23:54,480 --> 00:23:58,280
Officers can bring in expert witnesses

374
00:23:58,360 --> 00:24:01,720
who can present nearly any situation
as a potential threat.

375
00:24:01,880 --> 00:24:06,280
Dr. Bill Lewinski runs
the Force Science Institute.

376
00:24:06,440 --> 00:24:09,680
For years, he has testified
on behalf of police officers.

377
00:24:09,760 --> 00:24:14,160
Here is why it may be okay
to shoot someone that has a knife.

378
00:24:14,560 --> 00:24:17,080
Knives can be more dangerous.

379
00:24:17,200 --> 00:24:20,560
They don't have to be reloaded.
Can be used at close distance.

380
00:24:20,680 --> 00:24:26,320
A stab or a cut
can be extremely quick.

381
00:24:27,520 --> 00:24:31,040
That is not the motion you make
when you are stabbing someone.

382
00:24:31,720 --> 00:24:35,840
It's the motion you make when you are
a teenage magician finishing a trick.

383
00:24:36,320 --> 00:24:37,480
Is this your card ?

384
00:24:39,280 --> 00:24:43,520
There is no doubt, a knife
is a dangerous weapon.

385
00:24:43,680 --> 00:24:46,080
What if someone
doesn't have a knife ?

386
00:24:46,280 --> 00:24:50,240
Could force still be necessary
when someone is unarmed ?

387
00:24:50,920 --> 00:24:52,920
It's significant to know

388
00:24:53,000 --> 00:24:56,120
that unarmed does not mean
they're not dangerous.

389
00:24:56,680 --> 00:25:01,040
The fist may have been first weapon
human beings used against each other.

390
00:25:01,120 --> 00:25:06,560
I've measured strikes on human,
and the strikes can occur

391
00:25:06,640 --> 00:25:12,040
at a speed of 4, 5, or 6 strikes
in a second, some really hard.

392
00:25:13,040 --> 00:25:16,360
What is he talking about ?
The only time a fist

393
00:25:16,480 --> 00:25:19,960
is a match for a weapon is during
a game of rock paper scissors.

394
00:25:20,440 --> 00:25:26,280
It can be defeated by paper,
for reasons which make no sense.

395
00:25:26,760 --> 00:25:28,320
But that's not the point.

396
00:25:28,440 --> 00:25:32,360
Defendants are allowed
to call expert witnesses.

397
00:25:32,480 --> 00:25:36,520
Weird is, Lewinski has appeared
before grand juries,

398
00:25:36,640 --> 00:25:40,880
where prosecutors are supposed
to present their best case

399
00:25:41,000 --> 00:25:42,720
for an officer's indictment.

400
00:25:42,800 --> 00:25:45,080
Why would they let
Lewinski in there ?

401
00:25:45,160 --> 00:25:48,040
They're shooting
their own case in the foot.

402
00:25:48,200 --> 00:25:53,120
Presumably justified, because feet
were the second weapon ever invented.

403
00:25:53,880 --> 00:25:58,320
We've focused heavily on trials,
but in a perfect world,

404
00:25:58,520 --> 00:26:01,120
there would be enough
police accountability

405
00:26:01,200 --> 00:26:05,000
that the blunt instrument of a trial
would very rarely be necessary.

406
00:26:05,400 --> 00:26:06,880
How can we fix all this ?

407
00:26:07,400 --> 00:26:11,800
Body cameras have increased
transparency and trust.

408
00:26:11,880 --> 00:26:14,720
In Rialto, Calfornia,
after one year of using them,

409
00:26:14,800 --> 00:26:18,640
the number of complaints filed
against officers fell by 88 percent,

410
00:26:18,880 --> 00:26:21,840
and the use of force dropped
by around 60 percent.

411
00:26:22,160 --> 00:26:25,400
When Baltimore's trial run of a body
camera program ended,

412
00:26:25,480 --> 00:26:28,040
their commissioner
begged for their return.

413
00:26:28,240 --> 00:26:32,880
Officers want cameras. This is
a moment everybody wants cameras.

414
00:26:32,960 --> 00:26:37,480
I was speaking to some folks
and we had a couple police officers

415
00:26:37,560 --> 00:26:40,280
who were turning in their body cameras

416
00:26:40,400 --> 00:26:43,120
and were asking
"when can we get these back ?"

417
00:26:43,720 --> 00:26:46,840
Right, and these cops
aren't M. Night Shyamalan.

418
00:26:47,080 --> 00:26:51,440
If they plead to let them have
a camera, you should give it to them.

419
00:26:52,520 --> 00:26:53,560
Give it to them !

420
00:26:55,000 --> 00:26:59,840
Body cameras are one solution.
Other cities tried requiring officers

421
00:26:59,960 --> 00:27:03,200
to file separate reports every time
there's a use of force,

422
00:27:03,280 --> 00:27:07,360
or they've used early intervention
systems to spot problem officers,

423
00:27:07,440 --> 00:27:11,400
or they brought in outside prosecutors
to handle controversial cases.

424
00:27:11,520 --> 00:27:16,040
Police unions fiercely fight
any attempted reforms.

425
00:27:16,280 --> 00:27:20,360
Just listen to James Stewart, head
of the biggest police union in Newark,

426
00:27:20,440 --> 00:27:25,320
where the DOJ found three-quarters
of stops had no legal justification.

427
00:27:25,680 --> 00:27:29,960
To listen to him,
the police are being too scrutinized.

428
00:27:30,360 --> 00:27:32,640
I don't know
where the problem started,

429
00:27:32,720 --> 00:27:36,480
but there is an animosity
or a lack of trust.

430
00:27:36,640 --> 00:27:40,080
As soon as there's physical force
exerted by a police officer,

431
00:27:40,160 --> 00:27:43,160
everybody's got cellphones out
to catch us doing wrong.

432
00:27:43,440 --> 00:27:49,640
When you got the cop in the street
facing this negative opposition,

433
00:27:49,960 --> 00:27:53,400
does there come a point when
the police officer's going to say:

434
00:27:53,480 --> 00:27:58,600
"Maybe he doesn't have to go to jail.
I'll take a path of least resistance."

435
00:27:58,920 --> 00:28:02,960
"I'll put the blinders on at the corner
where the 10 guys are hanging out."

436
00:28:03,240 --> 00:28:08,480
There is a lot to unpack there:
first, threatening not to do your job

437
00:28:08,600 --> 00:28:11,520
because you've faced
public criticism is childish.

438
00:28:11,800 --> 00:28:14,560
You think Steven Seagal
gave up on his movie career

439
00:28:14,640 --> 00:28:16,680
because people said mean things ?

440
00:28:16,920 --> 00:28:19,960
Of course not ! Just this year,
he starred in End of a Gun,

441
00:28:20,120 --> 00:28:22,560
The Perfect Weapon,
The Asian Connection,

442
00:28:22,640 --> 00:28:25,600
Code of Honor
and Sniper: Special Ops. Why ?

443
00:28:25,760 --> 00:28:30,240
Because he's a fucking professional !
And he commits to his job.

444
00:28:32,040 --> 00:28:35,360
More importantly:
when you say you might ignore

445
00:28:35,440 --> 00:28:39,680
ten people hanging out on a corner,
yeah, maybe do that !

446
00:28:39,960 --> 00:28:42,280
That's not typically a crime.

447
00:28:42,680 --> 00:28:46,880
In some cases, ten people on a corner
is just a fucking yard sale.

448
00:28:47,880 --> 00:28:52,400
For many people, Stewart's argument
that for police to be effective,

449
00:28:52,520 --> 00:28:56,280
they need to be given broad leeway
to use force, is very appealing.

450
00:28:56,560 --> 00:29:00,600
It's especially appealing for those
of us who, for whatever reason,

451
00:29:01,000 --> 00:29:04,880
are confident that that force
won't be applied to them.

452
00:29:06,120 --> 00:29:09,600
But it is worth looking at
the actual cost of that tradeoff.

453
00:29:09,720 --> 00:29:14,440
Lack of trust in police accountability
leads to a lack of trust in police.

454
00:29:14,800 --> 00:29:17,800
We have reached the point
where there are schools

455
00:29:17,920 --> 00:29:22,960
who teach kids how to safely
interact with law enforcement.

456
00:29:23,560 --> 00:29:26,920
I want you to repeat after me.
I want you to say: "Officer !"

457
00:29:27,080 --> 00:29:29,080
"Am I free to go ?"

458
00:29:29,240 --> 00:29:33,200
One more time ! "Officer."
Am I free to go ?"

459
00:29:33,360 --> 00:29:35,920
The hope is, with this advice,

460
00:29:36,000 --> 00:29:39,880
teens can protect their rights
and maybe their lives.

461
